{"title_page": "Daniel Oliver (policymaker)", "text_new": "{{other people|Daniel Oliver}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Daniel Oliver\n|image_size = \n|caption = \n|birth_name    = Daniel Oliver\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1939|03|10}}\n|birth_place   = [[New York City]], United States\n|occupation    = Lawyer, writer, editor\n}}\n\n'''Daniel Oliver''' (born March 10, 1939) is a former executive editor of ''[[National Review]]'' from 1973 to 1976 and chairman of the [[Federal Trade Commission]] from 1986 to 1990.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://reaganlibrary.archives.gov/archives/speeches/1986/71686f.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=May 20, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118042101/https://reaganlibrary.archives.gov/archives/speeches/1986/71686f.htm |archive-date=January 18, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  He was chairman of the ''National Review'' board and a trustee of the magazine made so by [[William F. Buckley, Jr.]], founder of the publication.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2004/06/29/us/national-review-founder-says-it-s-time-to-leave-stage.html</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nOliver grew up in New York City.  He graduated from Harvard College [1964] and Fordham Law School.<ref>http://www.independent.org/aboutus/person_detail.asp?id=1636</ref>\n\n==Early career==\n\nFrom 1959 to 1962, Oliver served in the US. Army, stationed in California and Germany.\n\nIn 1965, he was a candidate for New York's state assembly while campaigning with William F. Buckley, Jr., in his New York City mayoral race.\n\nIn 1970, he worked as the Director of Research for [[James L. Buckley]]'s  successful New York senatorial race.<ref>http://www.thecandidamerican.com/?page_id=258</ref>\n\n==Reagan Administration==\n\nOliver was the General Counsel at the Department of Education from 1981 to 1983 under President Ronald Reagan.  He was General Counsel of the Department of Agriculture from 1983 to 1986 before becoming the Chairman of the Federal Trade Commission, a position he held until 1990.  He has an honorary doctoral degree from the Universidad Francisco Marroquin, an honor also bestowed upon former U.S. Ambassador [[Jeane Kirkpatrick]] and former Czech President [[V\u00e1clav Klaus|Vaclav Klaus]].<ref>https://www.ufm.edu/index.php/Honorary_Doctoral_Degrees</ref>\n\nThe Oliver-run Federal Trade Commission was known as one of the most anti-cartelist in the nation's history.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1987/04/27/daniel-oliver/d53bb117-8327-4de8-bcff-265ad9ee8093</ref>\n\n=== Milk Cartel Battle ===\n\nOne of Oliver's more famous battles took place from 1986 to 1987 when he led the fight to deregulate the price of milk in New York.\n\nHe awarded a \u201cNational Consumer Fleece Award\u201d to New York State Agriculture Commissioner Joseph Gerace for his support of the New York Milk Cartel which prevented a New Jersey dairy from selling milk in parts of New York City.  After Oliver, on the steps of City Hall at Christmas time, said Gerace had \u201cbrazenly upheld one of the most anti-consumer monopolies in the country\u201d Oliver wished the Commissioner a \u201cFleece Navidad.\u201d<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1986/12/23/fleecing-new-york-milk-consumers/7cece632-c729-4267-a6f7-413cc9adacdf</ref> The quip garnered Oliver headlines nationwide, and shortly afterwards the state\u2019s support for the dairy cartel collapsed, and Gerach resigned under pressure from the Cuomo administration.\n\n=== Health Insurance Cartel Battle ===\n\nOliver tried to repeal the insurance anti-trust exemption in health insurance markets in 1987, provoking a long and costly battle that he ultimately lost.<ref>https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=892&dat=19870626&id=E_NSAAAAIBAJ&sjid=hoIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5493,6480102&hl=en</ref>  Oliver's goal was to reduce the costs of American health insurance by removing barriers limiting competition\u2014in this case, being the first FTC chairman to propose the destruction of the [[McCarran\u2013Ferguson Act|McCarran-Ferguson Act]].  However, the issue has again received national attention in the 2016 presidential election.<ref>http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/election/article63786822.html</ref>\n\n=== Airline Competition Policy ===\n\nOliver defended airline deregulation in the 1980s and said it had allowed for more companies to enter the market and lower overall prices\u2014saving Americans $100 billion.<ref>https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2519&dat=19880209&id=LpZiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=63cNAAAAIBAJ&pg=4756,1179403&hl=en</ref>\n\n=== \"The Oliver Effect\" ===\n\nOliver's tenure at the FTC led some analysts to saying he sought to implement \"The Oliver Effect\" in product markets.<ref>\"Competition produces better products at lower costs. Regulations have made the health insurance markets of our states no different from the New York City milk market before chairman Oliver came along. Who but an ideologue can doubt lifting those restrictive regulations can produce the Oliver Effect in health insurance costs, too?\" Clark Judge, US News & World Report, July 9, 2012</ref>  In this way, Oliver also argued against foreign trade restrictions, saying in 1986 that they cost Americans $50 billion a year.<ref>https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1310&dat=19870214&id=B61QAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fOEDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6641,3088936&hl=en</ref>\n\n==Post-Reagan Administration==\n\nOliver is currently chairman Emeritus of the Pacific Research Institute, and chairman of the board of Education and Research Institute, an organization founded in 1974 by the late [[M. Stanton Evans]], one of the founders of the modern conservative movement in America.\n\nOliver also writes a column as \"The Candid American,\" which appears in a variety of publications including The Federalist, Daily Caller, Ricochet, The American Conservative, and The Washington Times.\n\nHe is also Senior Director of the Washington, D.C.-based White House Writers Group, a public policy and corporate consultancy.  Oliver focuses particularly on anti-trust.\n\nPreviously, he served as president of the conservative [[Philadelphia Society]], and was a senior fellow at the [[Heritage Foundation]], as well as chairman of the San Francisco-based [[Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy]].<ref>http://phillysoc.org/about/past-presidents/</ref><ref>http://www.whwg.com/principals/daniel-oliver/</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nOliver is fluent in Russian and is a U.S. Army-trained linguist.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://reaganlibrary.archives.gov/archives/speeches/1986/71686f.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=May 20, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118042101/https://reaganlibrary.archives.gov/archives/speeches/1986/71686f.htm |archive-date=January 18, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHe is married to Louise V. Oliver, US ambassador to [[UNESCO]] in Paris from 2004 to 2009.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Biography:  Louise V. Oliver\n| publisher = US Department of Stat\n| url = https://2001-2009.state.gov/r/pa/ei/biog/32314.htm\n| date = \n| accessdate = 21 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nOliver is a member of the [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church]].<ref>http://www.theamericanconservative.com/articles/extra-pope-denies-henry-viii-late-checkout-crisis-looms/</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[National Review]]\n* [[Federal Trade Commission]] \n* [[William F. Buckley, Jr.]]\n\n==References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oliver, Daniel}}\n[[Category:Federal Trade Commission personnel]]\n[[Category:National Review people]]\n[[Category:William F. Buckley Jr.]]\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Fordham University School of Law alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{other people|Daniel Oliver}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Daniel Oliver\n|image_size = \n|caption = \n|birth_name    = Daniel Oliver\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1939|03|10}}\n|birth_place   = [[New York City]], United States\n|occupation    = Lawyer, writer, editor\n}}\n\n'''Daniel Oliver''' (born March 10, 1939) is a former executive editor of ''[[National Review]]'' from 1973 to 1976 and chairman of the [[Federal Trade Commission]] from 1986 to 1990.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://reaganlibrary.archives.gov/archives/speeches/1986/71686f.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=May 20, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118042101/https://reaganlibrary.archives.gov/archives/speeches/1986/71686f.htm |archive-date=January 18, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  He was chairman of the ''National Review'' board and a trustee of the magazine made so by [[William F. Buckley, Jr.]], founder of the publication.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2004/06/29/us/national-review-founder-says-it-s-time-to-leave-stage.html</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nOliver grew up in New York City.  He graduated from Harvard College [1964] and Fordham Law School.<ref>http://www.independent.org/aboutus/person_detail.asp?id=1636</ref>  \n\n==Early career==\n\nFrom 1959 to 1962, Oliver served in the US. Army, stationed in California and Germany.  \n\nIn 1965, he was a candidate for New York's state assembly while campaigning with William F. Buckley, Jr., in his New York City mayoral race.  \n\nIn 1970, he worked as the Director of Research for [[James L. Buckley]]'s  successful New York senatorial race.<ref>http://www.thecandidamerican.com/?page_id=258</ref>\n\n==Reagan Administration==\n\nOliver was the General Counsel at the Department of Education from 1981 to 1983 under President Ronald Reagan.  He was General Counsel of the Department of Agriculture from 1983 to 1986 before becoming the Chairman of the Federal Trade Commission, a position he held until 1990.  He has an honorary doctoral degree from the Universidad Francisco Marroquin, an honor also bestowed upon former U.S. Ambassador [[Jeane Kirkpatrick]] and former Czech President [[V\u00e1clav Klaus|Vaclav Klaus]].<ref>https://www.ufm.edu/index.php/Honorary_Doctoral_Degrees</ref>\n\nThe Oliver-run Federal Trade Commission was known as one of the most anti-cartelist in the nation's history.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1987/04/27/daniel-oliver/d53bb117-8327-4de8-bcff-265ad9ee8093</ref>\n\n=== Milk Cartel Battle ===\n\nOne of Oliver's more famous battles took place from 1986 to 1987 when he led the fight to deregulate the price of milk in New York.\n\nHe awarded a \u201cNational Consumer Fleece Award\u201d to New York State Agriculture Commissioner Joseph Gerace for his support of the New York Milk Cartel which prevented a New Jersey dairy from selling milk in parts of New York City.  After Oliver, on the steps of City Hall at Christmas time, said Gerace had \u201cbrazenly upheld one of the most anti-consumer monopolies in the country\u201d Oliver wished the Commissioner a \u201cFleece Navidad.\u201d<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1986/12/23/fleecing-new-york-milk-consumers/7cece632-c729-4267-a6f7-413cc9adacdf</ref> The quip garnered Oliver headlines nationwide, and shortly afterwards the state\u2019s support for the dairy cartel collapsed, and Gerach resigned under pressure from the Cuomo administration.\n\n=== Health Insurance Cartel Battle ===\n\nOliver tried to repeal the insurance anti-trust exemption in health insurance markets in 1987, provoking a long and costly battle that he ultimately lost.<ref>https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=892&dat=19870626&id=E_NSAAAAIBAJ&sjid=hoIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5493,6480102&hl=en</ref>  Oliver's goal was to reduce the costs of American health insurance by removing barriers limiting competition\u2014in this case, being the first FTC chairman to propose the destruction of the [[McCarran\u2013Ferguson Act|McCarran-Ferguson Act]].  However, the issue has again received national attention in the 2016 presidential election.<ref>http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/election/article63786822.html</ref>\n\n=== Airline Competition Policy ===\n\nOliver defended airline deregulation in the 1980s and said it had allowed for more companies to enter the market and lower overall prices\u2014saving Americans $100 billion.<ref>https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2519&dat=19880209&id=LpZiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=63cNAAAAIBAJ&pg=4756,1179403&hl=en</ref>\n\n=== \"The Oliver Effect\" ===\n\nOliver's tenure at the FTC led some analysts to saying he sought to implement \"The Oliver Effect\" in product markets.<ref>\"Competition produces better products at lower costs. Regulations have made the health insurance markets of our states no different from the New York City milk market before chairman Oliver came along. Who but an ideologue can doubt lifting those restrictive regulations can produce the Oliver Effect in health insurance costs, too?\" Clark Judge, US News & World Report, July 9, 2012</ref>  In this way, Oliver also argued against foreign trade restrictions, saying in 1986 that they cost Americans $50 billion a year.<ref>https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1310&dat=19870214&id=B61QAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fOEDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6641,3088936&hl=en</ref>\n\n==Post-Reagan Administration==\n\nOliver is currently chairman Emeritus of the Pacific Research Institute, and chairman of the board of Education and Research Institute, an organization founded in 1974 by the late [[M. Stanton Evans]], one of the founders of the modern conservative movement in America.\n\nOliver also writes a column as \"The Candid American,\" which appears in a variety of publications including The Federalist, Daily Caller, Ricochet, The American Conservative, and The Washington Times.\n\nHe is also Senior Director of the Washington, D.C.-based White House Writers Group, a public policy and corporate consultancy.  Oliver focuses particularly on anti-trust.\n\nPreviously, he served as president of the conservative [[Philadelphia Society]], and was a senior fellow at the [[Heritage Foundation]], as well as chairman of the San Francisco-based [[Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy]].<ref>http://phillysoc.org/about/past-presidents/</ref><ref>http://www.whwg.com/principals/daniel-oliver/</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nOliver is fluent in Russian and is a U.S. Army-trained linguist.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://reaganlibrary.archives.gov/archives/speeches/1986/71686f.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=May 20, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118042101/https://reaganlibrary.archives.gov/archives/speeches/1986/71686f.htm |archive-date=January 18, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \n\nHe is married to Louise V. Oliver, US ambassador to [[UNESCO]] in Paris from 2004 to 2009.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Biography:  Louise V. Oliver\n| publisher = US Department of Stat\n| url = https://2001-2009.state.gov/r/pa/ei/biog/32314.htm\n| date = \n| accessdate = 21 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nOliver is a member of the [[Episcopal_Church_(United_States)|Episcopal Church]].<ref>http://www.theamericanconservative.com/articles/extra-pope-denies-henry-viii-late-checkout-crisis-looms/</ref>\n==See also==\n* [[National Review]]\n* [[Federal Trade Commission]] \n* [[William F. Buckley, Jr.]]\n\n==References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oliver, Daniel}}\n[[Category:Federal Trade Commission personnel]]\n[[Category:National Review people]]\n[[Category:William F. Buckley Jr.]]\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Fordham University School of Law alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daniel_Oliver_(policymaker)"}
